Title: The Dark Forest
Notes: Maybe low key the best of the series (in spite of the usual flaws). Dark Forest principle is one of the stickiest concepts from the novels.

Author: Moore, Alan
Title: Watchmen
Notes: Perhaps the best meta-take on superhero comics. Still not sure about how much time we spend inside the comic-in-a-comic with the pirates and the revenge guy and the O'Henry twist.

Author: Butler, Octavia
Title: Octavia E. Butler : Kindred, Fledgling, collected stories
Notes: Butler is still the queen. Library had this collection. Turns out it has a joint novelette winner (Bloodchild). Kindred was fine. Fledgling was fine. Speech Sounds was memorable. Also liked the one with the telepathic children and their teacher

Author: Kowal, Mary Robinette
Title: The Fated Sky
Notes: My favorite of the series! Idk, the journey to Mars does it for me. And the hints of Earth-side things we learn more about in the third book. I don't like how the framing removes a lot of potential drama beacuse we know how it will all end.

Author: Wells, Martha
Title: Exit Strategy
Notes: Right back on it, with a little extra helping of an ending suggesting an arc

Author: Le Guin, Ursula K.
Title: Tales from Earthsea
Notes: See Note for A Wizard of Earthsea

Author: Wells, Martha
Title: Rogue Protocol
Notes: Tone felt a little overdone at the beginning but it mellowed out and was still fun

Author: Lem, Stanislaw
Title: Solaris
Notes: Turn of the Screw in space? Strange, philosophical work. Kinda sticky, especially the ending and its dealing with meaning and the meaning of meaning

Author: Bester, Alfred
Title: The Stars My Destination
Notes: A pulpy adventure. Surprisingly readable

Author: Moore, Alan
Title: Swamp Thing
Notes: Super weird, but kinda fun. A villain who speaks in iambic pentameter. Surprisingly innovative art design (the hallucination issue).

Author: Lafrenais, Amanda,
Title: FTL, y'all! : tales from the age of the $200 warp drive
Notes: Impulse pick up. Surprisingly fun. The dog story is easily the stickiest

Author: Ennis, Garth
Title: Preacher
Notes: Fun overall. Didn't love the twist with Irish vampire guy at the end. Didn't love the late 90s "political correctness is bad, we'll offend everyone equally!" approach.

Author: L'Engle, Madeleine
Title: A Wrinkle In Time
Notes: Missed the window probably. Some alarming anti-collectivist stuff that was clearly motivated by Cold War nonsense

Author: Brooks, Max
Title: World War Z
Notes: Fun concept. No idea what the movie's deal is lol. Weird hyper-anti-semitism zionism stuff.

Author: Couch, Blake
Title: Recursion
Notes: Decent techno-thriller. Critchton-esque.

Author: Johnson, Kij
Title: At the mouth of the river of the bees : stories
Notes: Contains novellal joint winner "The Man Who Bridged the Mist". It was fine, cool and atmospheric. I also liked the title story, largely because Montana and vibes. The best story was the one about the trickster dogs tho, at the end! ITAP of the story about adjusting the electrostatic pressure or whatever

Author: Le Guin, Ursula K.
Title: Eye of the Heron
Notes: Not my favorite, tho anarchism and passive resistance are cool. Still fully realized because Le Guin is the queen

Author: Mignola, Mike
Title: Hellboy
Notes: Started off good with lots of nazi punching. The last 3 volumes didn't do as much for me.

Author: Skroce, Steve
Title: Post Americana
Notes: Impulse off-the-shelf pickup. Not very memorable

Author: Banks, Iain M.
Title: Consider Phlebas
Notes: Reddit (and others) love The Culture series. This chronologically first book is not really recommended as an entry point, but I did anyway. Didn't like it at all. The Ringworld section feels a lot like, uh, Ringworld. Pointless shock stuff with the drowning in shit and the cannibal cult. I guess I'll have to try Player of Games or one of the others but this one turned me off the whole franchise. It wasn't even that bad, maybe just overblown expectations?

Author: Kirkman, Robert
Title: Rick Grimes 2000
Notes: Very silly, didn't go anywhere.
